Aim
To write a program that demonstrates the use of an array of objects in C++.

Algorithm
Start the program.
Create a class with data members and member functions.
Declare an array of objects of the class.
Use a loop to input values for each object in the array.
Use another loop to display the values stored in each object.
End the program.

Program (C++)
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Student {
    int roll;
    float marks;

public:
    // Function to input student details
    void getData() {
        cout << "Enter Roll Number: ";
        cin >> roll;
        cout << "Enter Marks: ";
        cin >> marks;
    }

    // Function to display student details
    void display() {
        cout << "Roll Number: " << roll << ", Marks: " << marks << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    Student s[3];  // array of objects

    cout << "Enter details of 3 students:" << endl;
    for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
        cout << "\nStudent " << i+1 << ":" << endl;
        s[i].getData();
    }

    cout << "\nDisplaying Student Details:" << endl;
    for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
        s[i].display();
    }

    return 0;
}

Sample Output (Result)
Enter details of 3 students:

Student 1:
Enter Roll Number: 101
Enter Marks: 89

Student 2:
Enter Roll Number: 102
Enter Marks: 76

Student 3:
Enter Roll Number: 103
Enter Marks: 95

Displaying Student Details:
Roll Number: 101, Marks: 89
Roll Number: 102, Marks: 76
Roll Number: 103, Marks: 95

Result
Thus, the concept of array of objects is successfully demonstrated using a class and multiple object instances stored in an array.
